  "prompt": "Why is the Beatles song (originally from The Music Man) called \u201cTill there was you\u201d and not \u201cTill there were you\u201d?",
  "response": "The title of the song \"*Till There Was You*\" follows standard English grammar rules, which is why it uses \"was\" instead of \"were.\" The word \"there\" in this context functions as a dummy subject, and the verb agrees with the subject that follows it. In this case, the subject is \"you,\" which is singular here, so the correct verb form is \"was.\"\n\nThe phrase \"*Till there was you*\" implies that the speaker is referring to a singular person (\"you\") as the object of their affection or the focus of their experience. The verb \"was\" agrees with the singular subject. If the sentence were plural (e.g., \"Till there were you and me\"), then \"were\" would be appropriate.\n\nThe song, originally from Meredith Willson's *The Music Man* and later famously covered by The Beatles, uses this phrasing to emphasize the transformative presence of one person in the speaker's life. It\u2019s not about grammatical complexity but rather about poetic and emotional expression. The choice of \"was\" aligns with the singular, personal, and intimate nature of the sentiment conveyed in the lyrics.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
